{Of course, this classical miniature is one of my favorites. It demonstrates
castling as an attacking move, similar to what is found in some endgame
studies. Tartakower, seemingly winning a piece, soon finds that his opponent
has prepared a deadly double-check.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6
5. Qd3 e5 $2 {This move is a serious mistake, but one can only see that if he
already sees the checkmate.} 6. dxe5 Qa5+ ({Yes, technically the game still
would be playable after exchanging the queens. But if that is what you
sacrifice a central pawn for, you give up all winning chances and just have to
fight for a draw against an opponent who can decide if he rather wants a
positional or material advantage.} 6... Qxd3 7. cxd3 $5 (7. Bxd3 Nxe4 8. Bxe4
Nd7 9. Bf4 f6 10. exf6 Nxf6 11. Bd3 $16) 7... Nxe4 8. dxe4 Nd7 9. Nf3 Nc5 10.
Bc4 Nxe4 11. Be3 $16) 7. Bd2 Qxe5 8. O-O-O $3 Nxe4 (8... Qxe4 9. Re1 $18) ({
Black already had to turn to dangerously passive play.} 8... Be6 9. Nxf6+ gxf6
(9... Qxf6 10. Nf3 Nd7 11. Bg5 Qf5 12. Qxf5 Bxf5 13. Re1+ Be6 14. Nd4 Nc5 15.
b4 Na4 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Rxe6+ Kd7 18. Re4 Nc3 19. Rd4+ $18) 10. Bc3 Qc7 11.
Qg3 $1 Qxg3 12. hxg3 $16 {and White has a big advantage if he just continues
in a sane way, for example} Nd7 13. Ne2 O-O-O 14. Nf4 Bc5 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Bc4
Bxf2 17. Bxe6 Kc7 18. Bxd7 Be3+ 19. Kb1 Rxd7 20. Rxd7+ Kxd7 21. Bxf6 $16) 9.
Qd8+ Kxd8 10. Bg5+ Kc7 11. Bd8# 1-0

